Question 2

sum(is.na(flights$arr_time))

Checked for NA in the data, proceed to filter those out for analysis

flights <- flights %>%
  filter(!is.na(dep_time), !is.na(arr_time)) %>%
  mutate(
    #hours are currently in 515/2315, only wants to keep the hour
    dep_hour= floor(dep_time/100),
    arr_hour= floor(arr_time/100),
    
    dep_cat = case_when(
      dep_hour< 6  ~ "early morning",
      dep_hour< 12 ~ "morning",
      dep_hour< 18 ~ "afternoon",
      dep_hour<=24 ~ "evening"
    ),
    
    arr_cat= case_when(
      arr_hour< 6  ~ "early morning",
      arr_hour< 12 ~ "morning",
      arr_hour< 18 ~ "afternoon",
      arr_hour<=24 ~ "evening"
    )
  )

ggplot(flights, aes(dep_cat)) + 
  geom_bar(fill= "navy")
  labs(title="Departure Time Categories", x= "Period", y= "Count")
<ggplot2::labels> List of 3
 $ x    : chr "Period"
 $ y    : chr "Count"
 $ title: chr "Departure Time Categories"
ggplot(flights, aes(arr_cat)) + 
  geom_bar(fill = "maroon")+ 
  labs(title="Arrival Time Categories", x= "Period", y= "Count")

Average departure delay

avg_delay <- flights_weather %>%
  group_by(year.x, month.x, day.x) %>% 
  summarise(avg_dep_delay = mean(dep_delay, na.rm=TRUE)) %>%

Average departure delay by hour and origin

note: so looking back at summary, the max for dep_time is 2400 but max hour.x is 23 and max minute is 29; 2400 did not get translated into hour for flight data but did make it onto dep_hour (the one that I manually mutated by dividing dep_time by 100). For the sake of the primary question of looking at departure delay, I will be using the mutated dep_hour instead of hour.x

avg_delay_hour_orig <- flights_weather %>%
  group_by(origin, year.x, month.x, day.x, dep_hour) %>%
  summarise(avg_dep_delay_hour= mean(dep_delay, na.rm = TRUE), .groups = "drop") %>%
  arrange(desc(avg_dep_delay_hour))

Question 8

avg_delay_dest <- flights %>%
  group_by(dest) %>%
  summarise(avg_dep_delay= mean(dep_delay, na.rm = TRUE), n_flights = n(), .groups = "drop")

airports_delay <- airports %>%
  left_join(avg_delay_dest, by = c("faa" = "dest"))
library(leaflet)

pal <- colorNumeric("YlOrRd", domain = airports_delay$avg_dep_delay)

airports_delay %>%
  filter(!is.na(avg_dep_delay)) %>%
  leaflet() %>%
  addTiles() %>%
  addCircleMarkers(
    lng = ~lon, lat = ~lat,
    radius= 6,
    color= ~pal(avg_dep_delay),
    fillOpacity= 0.8,
    stroke= FALSE,
    popup= ~paste0(
      "<b>", name, " (", faa, ")</b><br>",
      "Avg dep delay: ", round(avg_dep_delay, 1), " min<br>",
      "Flights: ", n_flights
    )
  ) %>%
  addLegend(
    "bottomright",
    pal= pal,
    values= ~avg_dep_delay,
    title= "Avg Departure Delay (min)"
  )

Question 9

library(GGally)
flights_weather %>%
  select(dep_delay,temp, dewp,humid, wind_speed,precip, visib) %>%
  drop_na() %>%
  ggpairs(title = "Correlations: Weather Variables v Flight Delays")

All weather phenomena are statistically significant in their correlation with the departure delay. Among the 6, dew point and humid have the strongest correlation (>0.1)

Temperature and wind speed have the weakest correlation, suggesting that overall moist-related phenomena (humidity / rain / dew point) and the visibility that got affected as well affect the delay time the most.

Similar to step 5 in EAD:

flights_weather %>%
  filter(!is.na(precip)) %>%
  mutate(
    precip_bin = cut(precip,
                     breaks= c(-Inf, 0.1, 0.5, 2, Inf),
                     labels= c("0â0.1", "0.1â0.5", "0.5â2", "2+"),
                     include.lowest = TRUE)
  ) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x= precip_bin, y= dep_delay)) +
  geom_boxplot(fill= "skyblue", outlier.alpha = 0.2) +
  labs(title= "Departure Delays by Precipitation Level",
       x= "Precipitation (inches)",
       y= "Departure Delay (mins)")

As precipitation increases, median and range of delay grows, showing the impact of rains on flight delays

flights_weather %>%
  filter(!is.na(visib)) %>%
  mutate(visib_group= cut(
    visib,
    breaks= c(0, 2.5, 5, 7.5, 10),
    labels= c("0â2.5", "2.5â5", "5â7.5", "7.5â10"),
    include.lowest = TRUE
  )) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = visib_group, y = dep_delay, fill = visib_group)) +
  geom_boxplot(outlier.alpha = 0.2, show.legend = FALSE) +
  coord_cartesian(ylim = c(0, 120)) + ##hide outliers to better visualise
  labs(
    title= "Avg Departure Delay by Visibility Range",
    x= "Visibility (miles)",
    y= "Avg Departure Delay (mins)"
  )

The lower the visibility and higher the delay with a larger range.

flights_weather %>%

Similar trend observed with humidity, departure delay increases as humidity increases.

Overall, all the graphs supported the correlation analysis, that the moist-related phenomena have the strongest impact on the delay time.
